// @test regression/INV024-qualified-type-declarations
// @description A `series`/`simple` qualifier leading a type-annotated declaration (`series bool x = ...`), or following var/varip (`var series float c = ...`), must parse as ONE declaration. Previously the qualifier split the statement: inside a function body it truncated the body (spilling the remaining locals to top level, breaking tuple-return typing and producing undefined-variable cascades), and after var/varip the whole declaration was silently dropped. TV accepts all these forms (probed 2026-06-04). See investigations/INV024-qualified-type-declarations/notes.md.
// @expects parse: success
// @expects no-errors
//@version=6
indicator("t")

// Top-level qualifier-led declarations.
series float a = close
simple int b = 1
series bool flag = close > open

// Qualifier after var/varip.
var series float c = close
varip simple int counter = 0

// Comma-separated qualified units.
series int m1 = 1, series int m2 = 2

// Qualified declarations inside a function body must stay IN the body:
// the tuple return below only types correctly when the body is intact.
f() =>
    series bool found = flag
    series int size = b
    [found, size]

[x, y] = f()
q = x and close > open
plot(q ? 1 : 0)
plot(y + a + c + m1 + m2 + counter)
